            <summary>
              <p>2 fol.; Writing surface: parchment; Shelfmark: KFQ 21; Lines per page: 7; Dimensions: 122 x 183 mm (fol. 1), 120 x 190 mm, (fol. 2); Qurʾānic Text: Q 21:6-16; Script style: close to D.Va; Estimated date of production: 800-1000. [For technical reasons only the dimensions of fol. 1 are given above.] </p>
              <p>Cf. entry by François Déroche about fragment KFQ 21 (Déroche, <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">The Abbasid Tradition, London 1992</ref>, p. 103): "50 / Two folios / End of the 9th century AD or first half of the 10th / 12.2 x 18.3 cm (folio I) and 12 x 19 cm, (folio 2), with 7 lines to the page / <hi rend="italic">Material</hi> Parchment / <hi rend="italic">Text area</hi> 5.7 x 12.3 cm / <hi rend="italic">Script</hi> Perhaps style D.Va / <hi rend="italic">Accession no</hi>. KFQ 21 / The text on these two folios, <hi rend="italic">Sūrat al-anbiyāʾ</hi> (XXI), verses 6-16, runs consecutively, and the two folios must have been part of the first half of a quire, as the recto is the hair side in both cases. The text is written in black ink, with diacritical strokes; some of these are later additions, probably made when a later hand wrote over the letters. Red dots indicate the vocalization. The verses are not punctuated. A gold Kufic <hi rend="italic">hāʾ </hi>marks the end of every fifth verse, while the end of every tenth verse is marked by an ornament, now damaged, which may have been of type 2.A.II.”</p>
            </summary>
